<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05149h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05149h">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05149h"> 149(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> chi era Carneade?</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">When in 155 the famous embassy came from Athens consisting of Carneades the Academic, Critolaus the Peripatetic and Diogenes the Stoic, Cato was a prime mover of the decree by which they were removed from the city. Socrates was one of Cato&apos;s favorite marks for jests. And this is the man into whose mouth Cicero puts the utterances, but slightly veiled, of Greek wisdom! <small> Marcus Tullius Cicero, <a name="CATO" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CATO"><cite title="source">De Senectute</cite></a> (Edition of 1902) xxi</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: It. Who was Carneades? Proverbial for someone little known, after a phrase in Manzoni&apos;s I Promessi Sposi (The Betrothed, 1842), &ldquo;Carneade! <mark>Chi era costui?</mark>&rdquo; Carneades! Who was he?&rdquo; In fact, Carneades was a Greek skeptic philosopher from the 2nd century BC. </mm> </dd></dl>
